      • isNull

        default boolean isNull​()
        Returns true if this is a null value, the null value is not the same as a void value. A void value does not take up space in a collection, i.e. it has no size. A null however does and can optionally have a type also.
        Returns:
        true if this is a null value

      • isTrue

        default boolean isTrue​()
        Is true.
        Returns:
        true if this object is a boolean and is true

      • isVoid

        default boolean isVoid​()
        Is this object a void object? Void objects are a similar concept to nil in Objective-C, any operation on them results in a void value. However they take up no space in a collection. So are closer to the Java concept of void. If you wish to represent a non-existent value use void (think of this like a zero length array ). If you wish to represent a lack of value use null (think of this as a single length array with no assigned value.
        Returns:
        true if this is a void object
